File: A health department official collects samples from a man during a door-to-door COVID-19 testing drive. JOHANNESBURG -The General Gizenga Memorial Hospital formerly known as Stanger Hospital in KwaZulu-Natal has stopped accepting patients. This after nine mothers, two babies, four doctors, and a nurse tested positive for COVID-19. The 16 infected have been quarantined. READ: Ramaphosa in KZN to assess provincial response plans The testing of all staff and patients at the hospital is underway. Last month, two private hospitals in the province were temporarily closed after staff and patients tested positive for the coronavirus. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs